Electric Field of Point Charges

E⃗=14πϵ0qr2r⃗\vec{E}=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{q}{r^2}\vec{r}E=4πϵ0​1​r2q​r
ϵ0=8.85⋅10−12 C2/N m2\epsilon_0=8.85\cdot10^{-12}\text{ C}^2/\text{N m}^2ϵ0​=8.85⋅10−12 C2/N m2 is the permittivity constant

With multiple charges, F⃗on q=∑iF⃗i on q\vec{F}_{\text{on }q}=\sum_i\vec{F}_{i\text{ on }q}Fon q​=∑i​Fi on q​
Similarly, electric field is the vector sum of individual fields.

Consider a dipole with small distance sss between charges of +q+q+q and −q-q−q. It has an electric field. At a point $y\gg
s$, an approximation can be made to find the far field of the dipole
(Edipole)y≈14πϵ02qsy3(E_{\text{dipole}})_y\approx\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{2qs}{y^3}(Edipole​)y​≈4πϵ0​1​y32qs​
In particular, the dipole moment
p⃗=qs, from negative to positive charge\vec{p}=qs,\text{ from negative to positive charge}p​=qs, from negative to positive charge
is useful. The magnitude p=qsp=qsp=qs determines the field strength, and has SI units C m\text{C m}C m. Using this, the far field on the axis of the dipole moment
E⃗dipole=14πϵ02p⃗r3\vec{E}_{\text{dipole}}=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{2\vec{p}}{r^3}Edipole​=4πϵ0​1​r32p​​
where rrr is the distance from the center of the dipole

Electric Field Lines

instead of vectors, use electric field lines

  • continuous curve tangent to E⃗\vec{E}E
  • higher density means greater field strength
  • lines start from positive charges and end on negative charges

Electric Field of Continuous Charge Distributions

Let QQQ be the total charge (lowercase qqq is for individual point charges) of an object with length LLL. The line charge densityλ\lambdaλ is defined as
λ=QL\lambda=\frac{Q}{L}λ=LQ​
with units C/m\text{C}/\text{m}C/m
For a charged surface of area AAA, we define surface charge densityη\etaη to be
η=QA\eta=\frac{Q}{A}η=AQ​
with units C/m2\text{C}/\text{m}^2C/m2. (Volume covered in Ch.3)
We assume all objects are uniformely charged unless otherwise noted.

Using integration, the total charge becomes
Q=∫objectdQQ=\int_\text{object}dQQ=∫object​dQ
To integrate over a rod of length LLL, set the origin of the xxx-axis at one end and divide into small segments of size dxdxdx. Then due to the linear charge density, we have that dQ=λdxdQ=\lambda dxdQ=λdx. We integrate from x=0x=0x=0 to x=Lx=Lx=L, the length of the rod, so the integral becomes
Q=∫0LλdxQ=\int_0^L\lambda dxQ=∫0L​λdx
If λ\lambdaλ is constant, it can be factored out to yield Q=λLQ=\lambda LQ=λL. But if λ\lambdaλ were a function of xxx, integration can be used to find LLL.

Electric Field of a Ring of Charge


The ring of radius RRR lies in the xyxyxy-plane and the point on the zzz-axis. Since the component of the field along the xxx and yyy axes cancel out, we only calculate the zzz component, EzE_zEz​. The zzz-component of the field due to segment iii is
(Ei)z=Eicos⁡θi=14πϵ0ΔQri2zri(E_i)_z=E_i\cos\theta_i=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{\Delta Q}{r_i^2}\frac{z}{r_i}(Ei​)z​=Ei​cosθi​=4πϵ0​1​ri2​ΔQ​ri​z​
Regardless of the segment, rir_iri​ has the same value
ri=R2+z2r_i=\sqrt{R^2+z^2}ri​=R2+z2​
Thus,
(Ei)z=14πϵ0z(R2+z2)3/2ΔQ(E_i)_z=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{z}{(R^2+z^2)^{3/2}}\Delta Q(Ei​)z​=4πϵ0​1​(R2+z2)3/2z​ΔQ
The total field is the sum of the EiE_iEi​s
Ez=14πϵ0z(R2+z2)3/2∑i=1NΔQE_z=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{z}{(R^2+z^2)^{3/2}}\sum_{i=1}^N\Delta QEz​=4πϵ0​1​(R2+z2)3/2z​i=1∑N​ΔQ
Everything but ΔQ\Delta QΔQ can be factored out because they are all constants, and ∑ΔQ=Q\sum \Delta Q=Q∑ΔQ=Q, the total charge. Thus,
Ez=14πϵ0Qz(R2+z2)3/2E_z=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{Qz}{(R^2+z^2)^{3/2}}Ez​=4πϵ0​1​(R2+z2)3/2Qz​

As z≫Rz\gg Rz≫R

As the distance grows larger, the ring should approach a point charge.
If z≫Rz\gg Rz≫R
Ez=14πϵ0Qz(R2+z2)3/2≈14πϵ0Qz(z2)3/2=14πϵ0Qz2E_z=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{Qz}{(R^2+z^2)^{3/2}}\approx\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{Qz}{(z^2)^{3/2}}=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{Q}{z^2}Ez​=4πϵ0​1​(R2+z2)3/2Qz​≈4πϵ0​1​(z2)3/2Qz​=4πϵ0​1​z2Q​
This is the same as the field of a point charge at distance rrr.

The field is 000 at the center of the circle, positive in the positive zzz-direction, negative in the opposite.

The field reaches its maximum magnitude around ∣z∣≈R|z|\approx R∣z∣≈R

Electric Field of a Disk of Charge


Above is a thin disk of radius RRR with uniformely distributed charge QQQ.
The surface charge density is
η=QA=QπR2\eta=\frac{Q}{A}=\frac{Q}{\pi R^2}η=AQ​=πR2Q​
Same as above, we calculate the field at a point on the zzz-axis.
Since we know the field due to a circle of charge, we divide the disks into small rings of radius rrr and width Δr\Delta rΔr.
Each ring iii with radius rir_iri​ contributes to the field
(Ei)z=14πϵ0ΔQiz(z2+ri2)3/2(E_i)_z=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{\Delta Q_iz}{(z^2+r_i^2)^{3/2}}(Ei​)z​=4πϵ0​1​(z2+ri2​)3/2ΔQi​z​
Thus, the total field is
Ez=∑i=1N(Ei)z=z4πϵ0∑i=1NΔQi(z2+ri2)3/2E_z=\sum_{i=1}^N(E_i)_z=\frac{z}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\sum_{i=1}^N\frac{\Delta Q_i}{(z^2+r_i^2)^{3/2}}Ez​=i=1∑N​(Ei​)z​=4πϵ0​z​i=1∑N​(z2+ri2​)3/2ΔQi​​
From the surface charge density, the charge ΔQi=ηΔA=2πηriΔr\Delta Q_i=\eta\Delta A=2\pi\eta r_i\Delta rΔQi​=ηΔA=2πηri​Δr
From this we get
(Edisk)z=ηz2ϵ0∑i=1NriΔr(z2+ri2)3/2(E_\text{disk})_z=\frac{\eta z}{2\epsilon_0}\sum_{i=1}^N\frac{r_i\Delta r}{(z^2+r_i^2)^{3/2}}(Edisk​)z​=2ϵ0​ηz​i=1∑N​(z2+ri2​)3/2ri​Δr​
As N→∞N\to\inftyN→∞ this approaches the integral
(Edisk)z=ηz2ϵ0∫0Rrdr(z2+r2)3/2(E_\text{disk})_z=\frac{\eta z}{2\epsilon_0}\int_0^R\frac{rdr}{(z^2+r^2)^{3/2}}(Edisk​)z​=2ϵ0​ηz​∫0R​(z2+r2)3/2rdr​
Substituting u=z2+r2⟹du=2rdru=z^2+r^2\implies du=2rdru=z2+r2⟹du=2rdr and r:0→R⟹z:z2→z2+R2r:0\to R\implies z:z^2\to z^2+R^2r:0→R⟹z:z2→z2+R2,
(Edisk)z=ηz4ϵ0∫z2z2+R2u−3/2du=ηz4ϵ0[−2u−1/2]z2z2+R2=ηz2ϵ0[1z−1z2+R2](E_\text{disk})_z=\frac{\eta z}{4\epsilon_0}\int_{z^2}^{z^2+R^2}u^{-3/2}du=\frac{\eta z}{4\epsilon_0}\left[-2u^{-1/2}\right]_{z^2}^{z^2+R^2}=\frac{\eta z}{2\epsilon_0}\left[\frac{1}{z}-\frac{1}{\sqrt{z^2+R^2}}\right](Edisk​)z​=4ϵ0​ηz​∫z2z2+R2​u−3/2du=4ϵ0​ηz​[−2u−1/2]z2z2+R2​=2ϵ0​ηz​[z1​−z2+R2​1​]
Mutliplying through by zzz,

This is only valid for z>0z>0z>0. If z<0z<0z<0, the magnitude is the same in the opposite direction.

When z≫Rz\gg Rz≫R, we factor out z2z^2z2 from the denominator to get
η2ϵ0[1−11+R2/z2]=η2ϵ0(1−(1+R2/z2)−1/2)\frac{\eta}{2\epsilon_0}\left[1-\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+R^2/z^2}}\right]=\frac{\eta}{2\epsilon_0}(1-(1+R^2/z^2)^{-1/2})2ϵ0​η​[1−1+R2/z2​1​]=2ϵ0​η​(1−(1+R2/z2)−1/2)
When x≪1x\ll1x≪1, the binomial approximation (1+x)n≈1+nx(1+x)^n\approx1+nx(1+x)n≈1+nx can be used. Using it gives
η2ϵ0(1−(1+(−1/2)(R2/z2)))=η2ϵ0R22z2=Q/πR24ϵ0R2z2=14πϵ0Qz2\frac{\eta}{2\epsilon_0}(1-(1+(-1/2)(R^2/z^2)))=\frac{\eta}{2\epsilon_0}\frac{R^2}{2z^2}=\frac{Q/\pi R^2}{4\epsilon_0}\frac{R^2}{z^2}=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\frac{Q}{z^2}2ϵ0​η​(1−(1+(−1/2)(R2/z2)))=2ϵ0​η​2z2R2​=4ϵ0​Q/πR2​z2R2​=4πϵ0​1​z2Q​
describes the field of a point charge, as expected.

A Plane of Charge

  • electrodes: charged, flat surfaces like disks, squares, rectangles, used to steer electrons along the proper path.

If the distance zzz is small, we can approximate with an infinite plane of charge
From the equation above, we let R→∞R\to\inftyR→∞, then Eplane=η2ϵ0E_\text{plane}=\frac{\eta}{2\epsilon_0}Eplane​=2ϵ0​η​
Notice that this is dependent only on η\etaη, the charge density; in particular, it is not dependent on zzz. Thus, the field strength is the same everywhere.

The approximation is valid only if zzz is much smaller than RRR, so if that is the case, we can think of the field as a constant η/2ϵ0\eta/2\epsilon_0η/2ϵ0​ regardless of location or distance.

We do have to consider direction.
E⃗plane=(∣η∣2ϵ0,{away from plane if charge is +toward the plane if charge is −)\vec{E}_\text{plane}=\left(\frac{|\eta|}{2\epsilon_0},\begin{cases}\text{away from plane if charge is }+\\\text{toward the plane if charge is }-\end{cases}\right)Eplane​=(2ϵ0​∣η∣​,{away from plane if charge is +toward the plane if charge is −​)

Sphere of Charge

The integration is skipped, and will be derived later.
The field on a point outside a sphere of charge QQQ and radius RRR is the same as that of a point charge QQQ located in the center
E⃗sphere=Q4πϵ0r2r⃗ for r≥R\vec{E}_\text{sphere}=\frac{Q}{4\pi\epsilon_0r^2}\vec{r}\text{ for }r\ge REsphere​=4πϵ0​r2Q​r for r≥R

Parallel-Plate Capacitor

Two electrodes with equal and opposite charge arranged face-to-face a distance of ddd apart are called parallel-plate capacitors
Assume ddd is much smaller than the radius

Capacitors are charged by transferring electrons from one plate to another. The plate that gains NNN electrons has charge −Q=N(−e)-Q=N(-e)−Q=N(−e)

From the infinite plane field, we see that outside the capacitor, the fields cancel out. Inside, E⃗+\vec{E}_+E+​ and E⃗−\vec{E}_-E−​ point in the smae direction, so the field is large.
Thus, the net field inside is
E⃗capacitor=Qϵ0A, from positive to negative\vec{E}_\text{capacitor}=\frac{Q}{\epsilon_0A},\text{ from positive to negative}Ecapacitor​=ϵ0​AQ​, from positive to negative
and 0⃗\vec{0}0 outside.

In an ideal capacitor, the field is a uniform electric field as described above. In reality, there is a weak field outside the capacitor called the fringe field

Motion of Charged Particles

Force on particle qqq in a field EEE is Fon q=qE⃗=ma⃗F_{\text{on }q}=q\vec{E}=m\vec{a}Fon q​=qE=ma, so the acceleration is given by
a⃗=qmE⃗\vec{a}=\frac{q}{m}\vec{E}a=mq​E
This ratio, q/mq/mq/m, is the charge-to-mass ratio, which determines the acceleration
In a uniform electric field, E⃗\vec{E}E is constant, so acceleration is constant.

Dipole

A field affects a dipole by applying a F⃗+=+qE⃗\vec{F}_+=+q\vec{E}F+​=+qE force on the positive end and F⃗−=−qE⃗\vec{F}_-=-q\vec{E}F−​=−qE on the negative end. These cancel out to achieve a net force of F⃗net=0⃗\vec{F}_{\text{net}}=\vec{0}Fnet​=0. However, a torque is applied instead.

The torque is applied until equilibrium, when the dipole is parallel to the field. →\rightarrow→ become polarized, leading to an excess of charge on one end
The magnitude of the torque is τ=2×dF⃗+=2(12ssin⁡θ)(qE)=pEsin⁡θ\tau=2\times d\vec{F}_+=2(\frac{1}{2}s\sin\theta)(qE)=pE\sin\thetaτ=2×dF+​=2(21​ssinθ)(qE)=pEsinθ
When torque is aligned with the field, θ=0\theta=0θ=0 and τ=0\tau=0τ=0
In vector form,
τ⃗=p⃗×E⃗\vec{\tau}=\vec{p}\times\vec{E}τ=p​×E

In a nonuniform field once equilibrium is reached, the force on one end is slightly stronger, creating a net force, always toward the charge.
